              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A\to  B]]></fr:tex> be an arbitrary function. The <html:em><html:strong>image</html:strong></html:em> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> in defined to be the subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {Im}(f)\subseteq  B]]></fr:tex> spanned by the values of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex>:</html:p>
                <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
 \mathrm {Im}(f) = {\mathopen {}\left \{f(a)\,\middle \vert \,a\in  A\right \}\mathclose {}}
]]></fr:tex>
                <html:p>We may at times write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m_f\colon  \mathrm {Im}(f)\hookrightarrow  B]]></fr:tex> for the subset inclusion, which is an <fr:link href="/jms-00MO/" title="Injection" uri="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00MO/" display-uri="jms-00MO" type="local">injective function</fr:link>.</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>A function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A\to  B]]></fr:tex> also restricts to a function onto its image. In particular, we have:</html:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
 \begin {aligned}
   e_f&\colon  A\to  \mathrm {Im}(f)\\
   e_f(x) &= f(x)
 \end {aligned}
]]></fr:tex>
            <html:p>In fact, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[e_f]]></fr:tex> is a surjection. To see that this is the case, we fix an element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b\in  \mathrm {Im}(f)]]></fr:tex> and we must find an element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  A]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f(a)=b]]></fr:tex>. But by definition of <fr:link href="/jms-016D/" title="Image of a function" uri="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-016D/" display-uri="jms-016D" type="local">images</fr:link>, we know that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b]]></fr:tex> is of the form <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f(a)]]></fr:tex> for some <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> so we are done.</html:p>
            <html:p>Furthermore, function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A\to  B]]></fr:tex> is equal to the composite <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m_f\circ  e_f]]></fr:tex> as can be quickly seen: given <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  A]]></fr:tex> we compute <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m_f(e_f(a)) = m_f(f(a)) = f(a)]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
